@node c1541, Acknowledgments, Monitor, Top
@chapter c1541

VICE is provided with a complete stand-alone disk image maintenance
utility, called @code{c1541}.  You can either invoke it from the command
line or from within one of the VICE emulators, using the ``Run c1541''
command which will open a new @code{xterm} window with a running
@code{c1541} in it.

The syntax is:

@example
c1541 OPTIONS IMAGE
@end example

If some @code{OPTIONS} but no @code{IMAGE} are specified, @code{c1541}
runs in batch mode; otherwise, it attaches the @code{IMAGE} if present
and enters interactive mode, where you can type commands that are
executed when you press Enter (abbreviations are allowed).  As with the
monitor, file name completion and command line editing with history are
provided via GNU @code{readline}.  Use the command @samp{quit} to exit.

Notice that @code{c1541} always creates @code{X64} files, but can read
and write @code{D64} and @code{T64} files automatically, without the
need for any special options.

@menu
* c1541 commands and options::
@end menu

@node c1541 commands and options,  , c1541, c1541
@section c1541 commands and options

Each command-line option has an interactive-mode counterpart, that is
shown after it.  @samp{-} as a file name stands for standard input or
standard output, depending on the context.

@table @code

@cindex -attach
@item -attach  IMAGE
@cindex attach
@item attach  IMAGE
Attach the disk image @code{IMAGE} for use.  All the following commands
will refer to this image.

@cindex -detach
@item -detach
@cindex detach
@item detach
Detach the currently attached disk image.

@cindex -format
@item -format  IMAGE 'NAME,ID'
@cindex format
@item format  IMAGE 'NAME,ID'
Format the D64 disk image @code{IMAGE}, giving the specified label.  If
@code{IMAGE} does not exist, create it.

@cindex -gcr
@item -gcr  IMAGENAME ['NAME,ID']
@cindex gcrformat
@item gcrformat  IMAGE 'NAME,ID'
Create a GCR disk image; if @code{NAME,ID} is specified, format it.

@cindex -delete
@item -delete  IMAGE FILES...
@cindex delete
@item delete  FILES...
Delete  FILES  from @code{IMAGE}.

@cindex -list
@item -list  IMAGE
@cindex list
@item list
List files in @code{IMAGE}.

@cindex -validate
@item -validate  IMAGE
@cindex validate
@item validate
Validate the disk.

@cindex -copy
@item -copy  IMAGE OLDNAME1 [OLDNAME2...] NEWNAME
@cindex copy
@item copy  OLDNAME1 [OLDNAME2...] NEWNAME
Concatenate @code{OLDNAME1}, @code{OLDNAME2}.. into
@code{NEWNAME} on @code{IMAGE} (can be used to copy files).

@cindex -create
@item -create  IMAGE DUMP ['DESCR']
@cindex create
@item create  IMAGE DUMP ['DESCR']
Build @code{IMAGE} from raw dump file @code{DUMP} (i.e. convert
from @code{D64} to @code{X64} file).

@cindex -tape
@item -tape  IMAGE TAPEIMAGE [FILES...]
@cindex tape
@item tape  IMAGE TAPEIMAGE [FILES...]
Transfer @code{FILES} from @code{TAPEIMAGE} to @code{IMAGE}
(default is copy all files).

@cindex -read
@item -read  IMAGE 1541NAME [FSNAME]
@cindex read
@item read  1541NAME [FSNAME]
Extract @code{1541NAME} from the disk image into @code{FSNAME}
(1541NAME by default) from @code{IMAGE}.

@cindex -extract
@item -extract  IMAGE
@cindex extract
@item extract
Extract all files from @code{IMAGE}.

@cindex -write
@item -write  IMAGE FSNAME [1541NAME]
@cindex write
@item write  FSNAME [1541NAME]
Write @code{FSNAME} to @code{IMAGE} as @code{1541NAME}
(@code{FSNAME} by default). (works with @code{P00} files as well)

@cindex -block
@item -block  [DRIVE:] [TRACK] [SECTOR] [DISP]
@cindex block
@item block  [DRIVE:] [TRACK] [SECTOR] [DISP]
Show disk blocks in hex format.

@cindex -info
@item -info  IMAGE ['DESCRIPTION']
@cindex info
@item info  ['DESCRIPTION']
Show version information about @code{IMAGE}.

@cindex -unlynx
@item -unlynx IMAGE LYNXFILE
@cindex unlynx
@item unlynx LYNXFILE
Unlynx @file{LYNXFILE} into the image.

@cindex -zcreate
@item -zcreate  IMAGE DUMP ['DESCR']
@cindex zcreate
@item zcreate IMAGE DUMP ['DESCR']
Build @code{IMAGE} from a Zipcoded image made up of files called
@file{1!DUMP}, @file{2!DUMP}, @file{3!DUMP}, @file{4!DUMP}.

@end table

When more than one command is specified in batch mode, all of
them are executed in the same order they have on the command
line.


